If you meant something else by "run my project," or if you're trying to add more features like testing the actual summarization logic, let me know! (Note that as mentioned earlier, we experienced a build error for spacy on Python 3.14, so some specific summarization algorithms may not work until we downgrade Python or install the C++ build tools.)


> [!IMPORTANT]
> **GitHub Pages cannot host your full-stack application.**  
> GitHub Pages is designed for **static websites only** (HTML, CSS, and JS). Since your project relies on a **FastAPI backend** (Python), a **SQLite database**, and heavy **AI models** (HuggingFace/spaCy), it requires a server with a Python runtime.

To get your professional AI Summarizer live, I recommend using **Render** or **Railway**, which support full-stack applications with databases and Python backends.

### Recommendation: Deploy on Render (Free Tier)
Render is the easiest way to host this. I can help you prepare the project for Render. Here is what we need to do:

1.  **Add a `render.yaml` or `Dockerfile`**: This tells Render how to build your frontend and run your backend together.
2.  **Adjust the Port**: Ensure the backend listens on the port Render provides (using the `$PORT` environment variable).
3.  **Handle the Database**: Since SQLite files are wiped every time the server restarts on Render (ephemeral storage), we should ideally use a persistent disk or a external database if you want to keep data long-term.

### Would you like me to:
1.  **Prepare the project for Render/Railway?** (This includes creating the necessary configuration files and pushing them to your repo).
2.  **Only deploy the Frontend to GitHub Pages?** (Note: The summarization, login, and dashboard features will **not work** because the backend won't be running).

**Which approach would you prefer?**


✅ Project prepared and pushed to GitHub!

I have updated your code to be fully compatible with Render. All the necessary configuration is now in your repo.

🚀 Instructions to Deploy on Render:
Log in to Render.com and click "+ New" -> "Web Service".

Connect your GitHub repo: https://github.com/shaiknurullaT2/MINOR-PROJECT.git.

Configure the Service:

Name: summarize-ai (or anything you like).
Environment: Python 3.
Build Command: ./render-build.sh.
Start Command: cd backend && gunicorn -k uvicorn.workers.UvicornWorker main:app. (Note: You might need to add gunicorn to your requirements.txt if Render complains, but for simplicity, you can also use python main.py as the start command).
Important Note on Database: Render uses ephemeral disks for Free Tier Web Services. This means if the server restarts, any data stored in sql_app.db will be wiped.

To keep data forever, you would need a Render PostgreSQL database (Free for 90 days).
For now, your SQLite setup will work for testing, but data won't persist after a restart.
Your code is now live on GitHub and ready for the Render connection! Let me know if you need help with the specific Render dashboard settings.


🛠️ Build Error Rectified & Fixed!

The error occurred because Render was looking for requirements.txt in the root folder, but it was tucked inside the backend folder. I have fixed this and added extra configuration for a smooth deployment.

🌟 What I fixed:
Fixed Path Error: Added a root-level requirements.txt that correctly redirects Render to the backend dependencies.
Automated Setup: Added a render.yaml (Blueprint) file. Render will now automatically know exactly how to build and start your project.
Data Persistence: Configured a Persistent Disk in the Blueprint. Your user accounts and history will now survive server restarts!
Python Version: Pinned the version to 3.11 to ensure spaCy and other AI libraries install correctly.
🚀 How to Deploy Now (The Easy Way):
Go to your Render Dashboard.
Click "Blueprints" in the top menu.
Click "New Blueprint Instance".
Connect your repo: https://github.com/shaiknurullaT2/MINOR-PROJECT.git.
Render will automatically see the render.yaml file and set everything up for you (Build command, Start command, Disk, etc.).
Click "Apply" and wait for the green "Live" status!
Your code is already updated on GitHub. Just follow the Blueprint steps above and it should work perfectly!


